## 1 Overview

In this lesson you will learn how to use a DHT11 Temperature and Humidity Sensor to check the temperature and humidity in a room.

## 3 Component Introduction
### DHT11

DHT11 features a temperature and humidity sensor with a calibrated digital signal output. The DHT11 detects water vapor by measuring the electrical resistance between two electrodes.

There are two types of a DHT11 sensor that you may come across. One with three pins and a 10k resistor included, or the one included in this kit that does not have a pull up resistor inside it and has 4 pins.

The humidity sensing component is a moisture holding substrate with electrodes applied to the surface. When water vapor is absorbed by the substrate, ions are released by the substrate which increases the conductivity between the electrodes. The change in resistance between the two electrodes is proportional to the relative humidity.

Here is a graph to show you what this means:

To read the temperature the sensor uses a thermistor. A thermistor is a doped semiconductor. Semiconductors resistance drops with a rise in temperature as opposed to conductors (whose resistance rises with a rise in temperature).

So basically the DHT11, to read the temperature, reads the resistance of the thermistor. The steeper slope at lower temperatures of the thermistor means that you can calculate the resistance with better accuracy and hence the temperature will be more accurate.

## 5 Installing dependencies

To control the sensor we are going to use the Adafruit DHT11 Python library.

To install it we are going to clone a git repository. Enter the terminal and run the following command in a folder of your choice.

### git clone https://github.com/adafruit/Adafruit_Python_DHT.git

After we clone the repository change the directory in the newly downloaded folder:

### cd Adafruit_Python_DHT

Install the library dependencies with the following command:

### sudo apt-get install build-essential python-dev

Then to install the library run the following command:

### sudo python setup.py install

# 6 Code

The code is relatively simple, as the âmagicâ happens inside the library. We first need to import the libraries used, declare the type of sensor that we will work with, in our case we will use **Adafruit_DHT.DHT11**, and declare the pin used by the sensor and make it as an **INPUT**.

And we have the **while True** loop where we have a function **(Adafruit_DHT.read_retry())** that will give us the values for the temperature and humidity and then we will print those values in terminal (in case the values are not null). The **Adafruit_DHT.read_entry()** function requires two parameters. The first one is the type of sensor we are using, that is DHT11, and the second the PIN that we are using for data (in BCM numbering scheme). At the end of the code we have the instruction to clean all the ports used in this code.

"""
 * Credits: www.plusivo.com
 *
 * Lesson 14: DHT11
 *
 * This lesson is created for the lesson "DHT11",
 * where you will learn how to use a DHT11
 * Temperature and Humidity sensor.
 *
 * Do not forget to install the Adafruit_Python_DHT library
 * as shown in the guide!
 *
 * More details can be found in the guide.
 *
 """

#import the libraries
import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import Adafruit_DHT

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)

#name the type of sensor used
type = Adafruit_DHT.DHT11

#declare the pin used by the sensor in GPIO form
dht11 = 25

#set the sensor as INPUT
GPIO.setup(dht11, GPIO.IN)

try:
    while True:
        #make the reading
        humidity, temperature = Adafruit_DHT.read_retry(type, dht11)

        #we will display the values only if they are not null
        if humidity is not None and temperature is not None:
            print('Temperature = {:.1f}  Humidity = {:.1f}' .format(temperature, humidity))

except KeyboardInterrupt:
    pass

#clean all the used ports
GPIO.cleanup()
